<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-731-484  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 731 484.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Oct 2 1989 v8 n20 p93(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Agencies urged to beef up resistance to viruses.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Power, Kevin.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer virusesData SecurityGovernment AgencyUnited States. National Institute of Standards and TechnologyGuidelinesComputer Crimes.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Agencies Urged to Beef Up Resistance to VirusesandM;The National Institute of Standards and Technology is urging agencies todevelop better user education programs and contingency plans to reduce theirvulnerability to virus attacks.andM;In the first governmentwide guide on computer viruses, Computer Viruses andRelated Threats: A Management Guide, NIST officials called on agencies tomake security an integral part of any computer course and include computerviruses in their risk analyses and contingency plans.andM;Agency security procedures and control mechanisms have not kep pace with theexpansion of computing, the guide said.andM;&quot;With the widespread use of personal computers that lack effective securitymechanisms, it is relatively easy for knowledgeable users to author malicioussoftware and then dupe unsuspecting users into copying it,&quot; the guide said.andM;To beef up software security, NIST said agencies should establish validationprocedures to be followed before copies may be made.andP;  But NIST acknowledgedthat policies prohibiting copying of public-domain software could proveoverly restrictive and urged managers at least to buy software only fromreputable vendors.andM;Agencies also should keep records of where software is stored and ensure thatvendors can be reached quickly in case of emergency.andM;The guide said technical controls that limit access and manipulation areanother essential tool in reducing virus risks.andP;  Passwords and other types ofauthentication mechanisms should be used to limit user access, NIST said.andO;However, technical controls cannot guarantee complete protection, it said,warning that agencies must be aware of threats from authorized users whounderstand the safeguards.andM;Organizations with multiuser systems must be particularly vigilant, NISTsaid.andP;  Many multiuser systems can connect a small population to majornetworks and perform complex real-time operations.andP;  The guide said agenciesmust assign a dedicated system manager to each multiuser system and establisha strong organizational security policy.andO;</TEXT></DOC>